{{Infobox person |name = Nancy Eaton |image = |image_size = |caption = |birth_name = Nancy Alice Edward Eaton |birth_date = {{birth date|1961|05|28}} |birth_place = |death_cause = [[Stab wound]] |death_date = {{death date and age|1985|01|21|1961|05|28}} |death_place = [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]], Canada |nationality = [[Canadians|Canadian]] |ethnicity = |known_for = |education = |alma_mater = |employer = |occupation = |mother = Nancy Eaton Sr. |father = Edward Eaton }} '''Nancy Alice Edward Eaton''' (May 28, 1961 &ndash; January 21, 1985) was a Canadian heiress and a member of the prominent [[Eaton family]]. She was the great-great-granddaughter of [[Timothy Eaton]], founder of [[Eaton's]] [[department store]]s. She was the only daughter of Edward Eaton and Nancy Leigh (Gossage) Eaton of [[Toronto]].
==Murder== On January 21, 1985, Eaton was stabbed twenty-one times and then raped in her [[apartment]] in Toronto. An acquaintance of Eaton's, Ernest John Andrew Leyshon-Hughes,<ref name=board>{{cite web|url=http://www.bcrb.bc.ca/Decisions/all%20cases%20together/Leyshon-Hughes%20v.%20Ontario%20%28Review%20Board%29.pdf |title=Leyshon-Hughes v. Ontario |publisher=Review Board|accessdate=20 January 2018}}</ref> also known as Andrew Leyshon-Hughes, who was himself a member of the prominent Canadian [[William Osler|Osler]] family, admitted to murdering her, but was found not guilty by [[insanity defense|reason of insanity]]. He was indefinitely remanded to the custody of The Ontario Review Board.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/story/2001/02/13/010213eaton.html |title=Nancy Eaton's Killer Wants More Freedom|accessdate=2010-11-29 | work=CBC | location=Canada | date=13 February 2001}}</ref> In February 2001, Leyshon-Hughes was living at the [[Royal Ottawa Mental Health Centre|Royal Ottawa Hospital]] and was a student at [[Algonquin College]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/freedom-weighed-for-killer-of-heiress-1.274901|title= Freedom weighed for killer of heiress|accessdate=2014-11-02 | work=CBC | location=Canada | date=13 February 2001}}</ref> In 2005, Leyshon-Hughes was discharged from the psychiatric hospital into the community.<ref name=board/>
==In popular culture== In 2003, the television movie ''The Death and Life of Nancy Eaton'' was released. [[Jessica Paré]] played the part of Nancy. It airs on [[LMN (TV channel)|LMN]] in the United States and is based on the book ''A Question of Guilt'' by William Scoular.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0368672/|title=The Death and Life of Nancy Eaton| work=IMdb}}</ref>
